bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uelnileverstar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elnil Everstar</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_greenspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 176<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/28/02 2:05:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisbrellserilisdiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11215.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Question on loot rules for guilds</span><hr size=1> All these loot rules ideas have merit, but whatever you do, make sure you post it before the raid, and stick to it.  The biggest problems come from changing rules after a raid has started.<br>
<br>
 <p>Elnil Everstar 53rd Pathfinder<BR>GuildLeader and Officer of Aftermath of Darkness<BR>
Winterr Everstar's soulmate, 53rd Vicar<BR>Officer of Aftermath of Darkness<BR><a href=http://pub64.ezboard.com/barmageddon2>Aftermath of Darkness Board</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukhorenstonefall.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Khoren Stonefall</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_magentaspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elven Lovepony</span><br>  Posts: 1280<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/28/02 3:21:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisbrellserilisdiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11215.topic&index=7>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/jmlong/khoren_little.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Question on loot rules for guilds</span><hr size=1> Twiggie's point is the most important of all.  If you run your raids entirely in house, points seem to work very well.  They also work well only if you raid a LOT.  If you're going to have one raid a week, or two a month, or one a month, then it'll be completely disheartening to your members to realize that they have no chance, in the foreseeable term, to every get to the point where they could get anything out of attending your raids.<br>
<br>
Also, the point system must be fair.  Point systems that award bonus points to pullers and leaders and loot-masters and stuff are inherently unfair, because he who determines who fills those rolls controls who gets the points.  There are a lot of people who can pull, a lot who can lead, etc, etc.  If your system is one where anyone's favouritism can affect who gets more points, it will not be respected by your own members.<br>
<br>
You must be prepared to award points to your invites and to track them, or else you must run your raids ENTIRELY in house, because it is patently unfair to abuse people so the half of the raid that's in the point system gets recognized, and the half that isn't does not.<br>
<br>
The final problem, already stated above, is that point tracking requires tonnes of effort.<br>
<br>
My guild has an elaborate point system, and tackled this problem because we're blessed with Veranon, who made a fantastic database-based website that makes the tracking and managing of our point system very easy.  It took him a long time.  Points are awarded for attendance at the slaying of powerful mobs.  Points are spent on the items they drop, and whoever has the most points of the people interested in an item gets it--no random, no questions.  We have restrictions on a few items that forbid certain classes from getting them when members of certain other classes need them, but these are VERY few and far between, because teh system functions well on its own.  We value our points, and tend not to waste them on stuff that isn't REALLY GOOD for us, so we tend not to take items &quot;better suited for another class.&quot;  You can see something of how it works here:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.silentredemption.org/members.cgi?sort=total_dkp&asc=1">www.silentredemption.org/..._dkp&asc=1</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
and here<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.silentredemption.org/lootrotation.cgi">www.silentredemption.org/...tation.cgi</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
(You have to log in as a member to see all the point details about items, and as someone with corect permissions to see how the database is modified, but trust me, it's slick.)<br>
<br>
The whole thing is tied together, so that we use a database of existing mobs and their drops, with point values for items we have established ahead of time (or establish on the fly via a prescribed protocol when something new drops), and lists of our members and recruits to make for easy entry of raids, and automatic point calculation.  We use a private forum on our message board for people to make corrections if they were mistakenly not given points for a raid.<br>
<br>
Now...  That is well and good because it matches our size and play style, and because we were lucky enough to have Veranon, but it may not be right for all guilds.<br>
<br>
Previously, we did something else.<br>
<br>
We called the &quot;council system.&quot;  Every time we killed an uber mob, all of our present officers plus enough extra members determined by /random grouped together to make a 6-man council.  One of the council members collected names of everyone interested in a specific item that had just dropped, and then there was private discussion in the council, and then voting to see which of the interested characters received the item.  If there was a majority (4,5, or 6 votes) for one person, they automatically won the item.  If there was not, it was /random'ed 1 to 6, with each vote counting for one spot in the random.  (So if the votes were Khoren, Bob, Khoren, Jane, Dick, and Spot, the random would be 1-2 Khoren, 3 Bob, 4 Jane, 5 dick, 6 spot).<br>
<br>
This system accomplished the goals of making sure loot wasn't awarded by straight-random (which was unfair to people who raided a lot, particularly where first-time invites won uber loot), and that the loot went to people who could use it best (we used, particulary at that time, a lot of main-tank strategy for raiding, and we needed beefy warriors).<br>
<br>
However, although it worked fairly well for several months, and THEORETICALLY encouraged loot into the hands of those who &quot;deserved&quot; it (for all sorts of contributions to the guild, not just nightly participation), after awhile, people began to lose faith in it, believing that some members were discriminated against, and others were favoured.  This was inevitable.  The system is a solution to some issues, but can also cause some of its own.  Also, the system worked as long as it did because we raid virtually every night, and when you didn't win one night, you knew for sure you'd win sometime in the next few weeks or month or so.<br>
<br>
Anyway, in its deepest stages of decline, the system damaged some of the trust in our guild, I believe, and certain poisoned the atmosphere now and then.<br>
<br>
So our migration to points seems, in hindsight, to be particularly effective.  I freely admit that I was opposed to the point system in principle when it was proposed, and now I am quite a fan of it.  It allows only one determining factor in the awarding of loot:  Your raid attendance.  To us, that is an important measure, and it IS a measure of how much time you give to the guild through raids.  Also, we expect all of our members to do their best on raids, so we don't consider any one person's attendance to be more valuable than another's.  If you made a point system for yourself, you may award bonus points for non-raid activities, and that is well and good, but we do not do that.  We try to keep the system very objective, allowing no one's discretion to enter into the awarding of points, so all members are on a level playing field.<br>
<br>
The natural argument is that this is not fair to people who cannot raid all the time because of other commitments, but, as a semi-active player, I can tell you, it's very fair to award loot that way.  I am way down on our point list, which means I can't get the BEST items, but I can still get good items, or items after the really active members (who deserve them and need them more) already have them.<br>
<br>
So, I can only relate five personal experiences with loot:<br>
<br>
1) Open random in a smaller-scale guild.  This tended to cause the odd result that seemed unfair because members who were rarely active could win the very rare uber loots that we got.<br>
<br>
2) A point system with discretion (points awarded for pulling, leading, etc) in a smaller-scale guild.  The majority of members who talked to me about this considered this to be a failure.  It serves the leaders of the guild in a way that some other members may find alienating or unfair.<br>
<br>
3) Open random in a hyper-active large-scale guild.  This discouraged us from ever taking invites, and made us less polite and more exclusionary than when we used:<br>
<br>
4) A council system in a hyper-active large-scale guild.  This was much preferable for quite some time.  My first loot I won with SR was one of the first bile chokers to drop from CT, and that was before I was a member.  We used this system to reward members AND very active recruits, but in the end, (after about 9 or 10 months) it began to decline and arouse suspicion and ill feelings, and so we turned to:<br>
<br>
5) A raid participation point system in a hyper-active large-scale guild.  And I believe, after about 2 or 3 months of experience with it, that this is working well and fairly.  And let me tell you, it sure encourages participation. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But, also, honestly, at the same time, it allows members to feel less guilty about not participating because they can rationalize that they are taking nothing away, loot-wise, for their absence.  This makes it possible to take guilt-free breaks when they're needed.<br>
<br>
Khoren Stonefall<br>
Level 60 Crusader of Marr<br>
Silent Redemption <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukykr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kykr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/28/02 3:49:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisbrellserilisdiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11215.topic&index=8>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Question on loot rules for guilds</span><hr size=1> Wow - thanks Khoren and everyone else that has replied.  <br>
<br>
You have brought up some good points and some ideas our officers need to discuss.  <br>
<br>
If we decide to implement the point system it will be very strict - awarding points for being on time, each hour on the raid and completing the raid - possibly an extra point for those that are there from start to finish.  The last thing we want to do is hand out points left and right.  <br>
<br>
I have heard of a concept of silent bidding/auction but no one has been able to explain to me what the benefits of this type of system is.  I am thinking it's used if something nice drops - those that want to use their points to get the item send a tell to the Loot Supervisor stating how many points they wish to bid.  The person that bids the highest wins.  However, what if any, are the benefits of doing this silently?  Seems to me it's opening the system up to be abused.  <br>
<br>
Thanks again for the input - you guys are great!<br>
<br>
