<br>
I thank you all for your ideas/input.  I was asked to gather information on looting and you all came through.  We are planning an officer then guild meeting to discuss the options and will make a final decision then.<br>
<br>
The idea of drops going to highest character (providing that person raids often) intrigues me.  The logic behind it makes a lot of sense - if your highest players have the better equipment, the more chance they have at staying alive, the more successful raids you have, the more chance of equipment/items dropping - the guild ends up in a really nice cycle.  If I'm understanding this concept correctly this is what could/would happen during a raid. Guild is raiding and a really good melee bp drops - main tank's (the guy that is our tank if he is there) bp is no where near as good -  the bp automatically goes to him.  What do you do if a lesser item drops - how would it be distributed? <br>
<br>
Another question came up last night - do all guilds require their members to pay raid fees?  For those that don't - how do you cover the cost of peridots/reagents for chanters/clerics?  Right now on our baby raids we haven't charged people - we can make enough plat from the raid to cover the cost and any extra goes into the guild vault for future raids.  In most guilds I've been involved with they have charged for raids - Fear/Hate/Kael 100pp or 10 peridots - PoA/Growth 250pp or 25 peridots.  My main use to be a necro and while I would always pay the fee I would never receive any benefit of being buffed.  I only raided a few times and it really seemed the guild leaders/raid leaders would walk away with extra stacks of reagents.  I'm probably in the dark in this matter but if you have 30 people on a raid - charge those 30 people 100pp/10peridots - Do the clerics/chanters really go through 300 reagents?  Maybe someone can enlighten me on this <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Again thanks for taking the time to answer my questions - I can't begin to tell you how much help the information you've shared has been.<br>
