<br>
Perhaps in the future we will move to a point system, but right now BI awards major loots and all epic items as the council sees fit (based on level, raid participation, and in the case of epic items, how close to completion)<br>
<br>
We also have a &quot;hand me down&quot; clause, where if a member wins something on our raid, and then wins something better later, you're required to pass down your old loot to someone else in the guild. (if it's tradeable of course) It's a win-win situation for all involved. Haven't had any complaints with the system so far, so we're doing something right. <p><img src="http://www.fftrealm.com/content/pics/line.gif" width="300" height="2"><p><a href="mailto:MiriamelePrester@aol.com?subject=EZBoard"><img src="http://www.fftrealm.com/content/pics/miri.jpg" width="300" height="42" border="0"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubludraptor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BludRaptor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/30/02 9:54:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisbrellserilisdiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11215.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Question on loot rules for guilds</span><hr size=1> The DKP system is an incredible system. It works very well, especially for people who raid at least 3 times a week. When loot is counciled or randomed, then people have the attitude of only attending something that drops loot that they want. With the DKP system, people will show up no matter what, to get points for themselves, and to help their fellow guildies and friends help as well. In the end, DKP system is a lot more maintenance but in my opinion, is well worth it.<br>
<br>
People are gonna get upset when say ToV armor is randomed and an inactive level 54 paladin wins plate legs over a highly active 60 warrior or something. Also, council is hard to do because there's nothing &quot;behind&quot; it that people can see why who won what, it's just using good judgement really. But a few times they could make unfair decisions or people will think it's more of a popularity contest. It works well though 90% of the time and doesn't require nearly as much book-keeping.<br>
<br>
Also, i'm not sure if SR does this or not, but there's a possible rule in the DKP system called a weekly adjustment, where it brings all the members close to the average or median points by a very small percentage (maybe 1% or so). This way, it will give the inactive members a headstart when they get back (but they'll still need to work hard). And will keep the extremely active members not so powerful where they can win anything they want whenever they want (tho they'll still get a good deal of what they need). <br>
